<br>
It's difficult to get non players to understand the appeal of EverQuest.  I have a coworker that insists she's doing me a favor by making me work late.  <br>
<br>
Folks say "It's just a game".  I've always hated this.  It's not.  It's not Pac Man or Might & Magic (gawd, one time my sister demanded that I pause EQ in the middle of a raid so I could talk to her, "Um, hon, the 2000 other players would get seriously pissed if I did that.").  If you find yourself on Norrath unguilded, maybe it's easy to walk away.  But once you've joined a guild you've joined a Community.  If you stay with/in that community, it's because it usually adds some value to your experience.  And that value, despite it's "digital" aspect, can be a valid priority for you.  As much as a weekly golf habit or bridge with the ladies.  <br>
<br>
That said, would you risk your relationship over golf or bridge?  Would your partner?  These, of course, aren't easy answers.  I've seen people stop playing because a lover got too upset (I know one couple that is now playing DAoC together).  I've seen spouses sucked in to EverQuest because of the same issues.  I've also heard from people that, while leaving EQ behind them was painful, they've come to not miss it.  <br>
<br>
I know I haven't been helpful, giving advice and such.  I really can't give you any advice here.  I don't know you or your partner well enough to make assumptions about your value systems. All I can do is highlight some perspectives from a fellow EverCrack Addict.  If you feel the need to rail at somebody while you're suffering through this conflict, my e-mail's RawBear@twors.net, my AIM handle is RawBearNY and you can always /tell me in game.  I can listen.  Can't really give advice, but can listen. :) <p>Ray,<BR>
Kenwein Woodmaster<BR>
51st Level Wood Elf Druid<BR>
